<dl id="n06154k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06154k">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06154k"> 154(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ convinces of sin <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n06154k"><li>FW 62.20 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n06154k">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n06154k">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n06154k">MS BL 47471b-10v</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:151 <a name="c20d" href="../../FF/fdra/cda.htm#c20d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/c20d.htm#n06154k">Draft: I.3&sect;2.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[from the Eighth Article of the Creed]</font> The Greek word parakletos, Comforter, is elsewhere rendered Advocate; the Holy Ghost is, like Christ, an Advocate with the Father. He also <mark>convinces of sin</mark>; He is a teacher, guiding into all truth, and leading in the way of holiness; He restrains from sin, by His indwelling. <small> Anonymous, <a name="ATCC" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ATCC"><cite title="source">Analysis of the Church Catechism</cite></a> (1879) 24</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
